Result: false  
Justification:  
The P-type arguments attempt to prove that Melissa must earn recognition, but their reasoning relies on misinterpreting modal terms. Specifically, the freshness condition states that if Melissa preserves freshness, she *can* either create unique flavors or earn recognition (but not both) – this expresses possibility, not necessity. Even if all premises are accepted (Melissa preserves freshness, cannot create unique flavors due to attracting customers), it does not logically force her to earn recognition; she might simply not actualize either possibility. Since the P arguments’ conclusions are not logically necessary given the premises, C11 is not satisfied.